    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned i need to set up an escrow account for this house i'm buying in toronto. i'm kinda confused. whats escrow actually and why do i need it for the closing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Eh, an escrow account is basically a neutral third-party vault where the money sits while the deal is happening, but honestly, it's just a fancy way of saying the bank or title company is holding the funds until the deal is done so nobody gets ripped off. You need it because if you just wired the money straight to the seller, they might run away with it before the deed is transferred, and if the seller didn't deliver the keys, you'd be stuck with a house you can't enter. It's like a trusty little goblin guard who won't let anyone touch the gold until the contract is signed and sealed.\n\nThink of it like this: the escrow agent is the big, grumpy goblin who sits on a pile of gold coins in the middle of the room, refusing to let the buyer take the coins until the seller promises to hand over the deed, and the seller refusing to hand over the deed until the buyer promises to pay the coins. It's a classic goblin standoff where the goblin holds the keys to the kingdom until both sides agree to the terms. Without the goblin, the buyer might pay the seller and then find out the seller sold the house to someone else, or",
      "source": "target",
